- VSCode Version: Code 1.5.3 (5be4091987a98e3870d89d630eb87be6d9bafd27, 2016-09-22T08:50:42.185Z)
- OS Version: Windows_NT ia32 10.0.14393

Steps to Reproduce:

In Typescript:

```
class Dummy
{
   // If I remove the newline after 'dummyMethod', highlighting of the next 'public' keyword works.
   public dummyMethod
   (
      // Some parameters.
   )
   {
      // Function body.
   }

   //  The 'public' keyword will not be highlighted.
   public anotherDummyMethod() {}
}
```

I would like to update a config value by first getting it and then calling update:

``` typescript
const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('files.autoSave');
config.update('', 'afterDelay', true);
```

First of all, it seems weird that I have to provide a key in the update method because all I want is to update the config value I received previously. So I would assume the key to be optional in that case.

Second, it does not work at all and I always end up with: `Unable to write to the configuration file (Unknown Key)`

The only thing that does work is:

``` typescript
const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('files');
config.update('autoSave', 'value', true);
```
